  "overview": {
    "h2": "Mercedes E‑Class W212 — Overview",
    "intro": "The W212 is the fourth‑generation E‑Class, launched in March 2009 as the successor to the W211. It introduced a more angular design language with quad‑headlights replaced by single‑lamp units, a longer wheelbase, and a range of new engines including the OM651 four‑cylinder diesel family. A major 2013 facelift brought significant styling changes, improved engines, and new safety features — reported to be the most significant mid‑cycle refresh Mercedes had ever undertaken. The W212 was succeeded by the W213 in 2016.",
    "keyFacts": "Platform: W212 (Mercedes‑Benz fourth‑generation E‑Class platform) • Predecessor: W211 (third‑generation E‑Class) • Successor: W213 (fifth‑generation E‑Class) • Sibling body styles in this generation: S212 (estate), C207/A207 (coupé/convertible — based on W204 C‑Class platform)",
    "marketIntelligenceLine": "The W212 E‑Class generated significant UK engine enquiry demand in 2025 [MB‑VERIFIED], concentrated on the OM651 diesel and M271/M274 petrol variants as these cars enter their second decade of service."
  },
  "bestWorstEngines": {
    "items": [
      {
        "slot": "Best Diesel Overall",
        "engine": "OM651 (E 220 CDI / BlueTEC)",
        "quote": "“The 2.1‑litre four‑cylinder diesel is the W212's most dependable engine — proven across millions of miles in taxi and fleet service, with genuine 200,000+ mile potential. The 170 PS version delivers effortless performance without the V6 diesel's higher running costs.” Who it’s for: Buyers who want diesel economy and six‑figure mileage potential.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      },
      {
        "slot": "Best Petrol Overall",
        "engine": "M274 (E 200 / E 250, 2013–2016)",
        "quote": "“The 2.0‑litre turbo four is a significant improvement over the M271 — smoother, more efficient, and free of the older engine's camshaft adjuster issues. 211 PS in the E 250 is plenty for executive duties.” Who it’s for: Buyers who want a modern petrol E‑Class without V6 running costs.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      },
      {
        "slot": "Highest Risk",
        "engine": "M272 V6 (E 300 / E 350 / E 350 CGI, 2009–2011)",
        "quote": "“The M272's balance shaft sprocket wear is this generation's defining risk — a design flaw that can lead to catastrophic engine failure. Mercedes acknowledged the issue but didn't extend the warranty as widely as with later engines.” Who it’s for: Buyers who understand the risk and have documented balance shaft history.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      },
      {
        "slot": "Most Expensive Failure",
        "engine": "M156 (E 63 AMG, 2009–2011)",
        "quote": "“The 6.2‑litre naturally aspirated V8 is a masterpiece — but punishing to repair. Head bolt failure, camshaft adjuster wear, and tappet issues are well‑documented. A full replacement runs well into five figures.” Who it’s for: AMG enthusiasts with deep pockets and full service history.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      },
      {
        "slot": "Best Value",
        "engine": "OM651 (E 220 CDI)",
        "quote": "“The entry‑level diesel shares the same robust OM651 architecture as the more powerful versions — but costs less to buy and less to replace. Timing chain and injector seal maintenance are the only real demands.” Who it’s for: Buyers who want diesel economy on a tighter budget.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      },
      {
        "slot": "Most Overlooked",
        "engine": "M276 V6 (E 350, 2012–2016)",
        "quote": "“Often overshadowed by the V8 models, the M276 V6 is actually the most refined petrol in the range — smoother than the M272, more reliable than the M156, and with 306 PS in the E 350, genuinely quick. It’s the sweet spot of the W212 petrol range.” Who it’s for: Buyers who want V6 refinement without AMG running costs.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      }
    ]
  },
